result.execSummary:
The defendant Al Kentrail Shack was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Al Kentrail Shack in court with attorney Daniel H Sanders.  Defendant Al Kentrail Shack in custody.  Sarah McNutt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the state, defense and defendant.
The Court ordered the Defendant to serve 90 days in the House of Correction, concurrent with count 1 in 15CF2896 with credit for 0 days time served.    The court orders defendant to pay all applicable costs, fees, assessments and surcharges and restitution of $250.00 to victim, DH for damaged door,  as a condition of EXTENDED SUPERVISION as imposed in count 1 in 15CF2864 and failure to do so will result in entry of civil judgment.

Defendant Al Kentrail Shack in court with attorney Daniel H Sanders.  Defendant Al Kentrail Shack in custody.  Sarah McNutt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  AS to count 1:    Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead NO CONTEST.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed in 15CF2864.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered.
Count 2 is ordered dismissed and read in for sentencing.  Defendant is remanded pending sentencing on 1-5-2016.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for January 5, 2016 at 08:15 am.
